      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nSince we use calendars daily, we often do not pay attention to how they were created and, above all, how they are used.\n\nIn this text, we wish to draw attention to some details that often lead people to conclusions that, although they do not represent their own realities, give the impression of being the \"only\" conclusions. To make this even clearer, we will begin with a reflection.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: The periods</b><br /><br />Archaeological and anthropological findings indicate that we, <i>Homo sapiens</i>, had a common origin in Africa approximately 300,000 years ago (<htcite0>). Does this mean that we all use the same calendar?<br /><br />Does that calendar have the same starting point? In other words, are we all in the year 300,000?<br /><br />Why should we consider the emergence of our species as the starting date? Why not consider the beginning of the Universe, which occurred nearly 14 billion years ago (<b>Figure 1</b>) (<htcite1>)?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
